[The press release above is a timely, detailed, useful guiding document for which OIE deserves to be commended.

OIE's requirements for the immediate notification of LPAI, as laid out in its terrestrial Code chapter 10.4 (http://tinyurl.com/bodurqc), are restricted to "poultry." "Poultry" is defined as: "all domesticated birds, including backyard poultry, used for the production of meat or eggs for consumption, for the production of other commercial products, for restocking supplies of game, or for breeding these categories of birds, as well as fighting cocks used for any purpose."

The Code further indicates that "birds that are kept in captivity for any reason other than those reasons referred to in the preceding paragraph, including those that are kept for shows, races, exhibitions, competitions or for breeding or selling these categories of birds as well as pet birds, are not considered to be poultry."

China's initial notification of LPAI H7N9, in a pigeon, as submitted to the OIE on 4 Apr 2013, was required since this case was related to "a pigeon for consumption." As to the new, zoonotic LPAI H7N9 strain infections in racing pigeons and in other birds which are not "poultry," including wild birds, OIE may consider facilitating the legal grounds which will require their (recommended) notification. As a zoonotic/emerging disease?!

Information on surveillance in wild birds, including the number of samples collected, species sampled, locations covered, the number of tests performed/completed and their results, is anticipated soon. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1zaU.]
